Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law contains the Windsor Park Environmental Justice Act, which
2 establishes a program for the relocation of persons residing in the Windsor Park
3 neighborhood of the City of North Las Vegas whose residences have been damaged
4 by the sinking of the ground beneath the residences. (Chapter 531, Statutes of
5 Nevada 2023, at page 3538) Under the Act, the Housing Division of the
6 Department of Business and Industry is required to establish and administer a
7 program by which the owner of a single-family residence in the Windsor Park
8 neighborhood who owns the residence on July 1, 2023, may exchange the residence
9 in the Windsor Park neighborhood for a new residence constructed in accordance
10 with the Act. (Section 9 of chapter 531, Statutes of Nevada 2023, at page 3540)
11 This bill makes revisions to the Act.
12 Section 1 of this bill requires the Housing Division to: (1) adopt regulations to
13 carry out the provisions of the Act, including, without limitation, regulations
14 governing certain specific topics; and (2) provide quarterly reports to the Interim
15 Finance Committee concerning the implementation of the provisions of the Act.
16 Section 2 of this bill clarifies the boundaries of the Windsor Park neighborhood
17 for the purposes of determining the owners of single-family residences or vacant
18 lots who are eligible to participate in the program.
19 Section 3 of this bill: (1) requires that, to be eligible to participate in the
20 program, an owner of a single-family residence or vacant lot in the Windsor Park
21 neighborhood must have owned that single-family residence or lot on
22 December 31, 2023, rather than July 1, 2023; (2) authorizes a person who is the
23 owner of a vacant lot in the Windsor Park neighborhood and who was the owner, or
24 is the descendant of the former owner, of a single-family residence that was
25 formerly located on that vacant lot in the Windsor Park neighborhood to participate
26 in the program by exchanging the vacant lot for another vacant lot in an area as
27 near as reasonably practicable to the Windsor Park neighborhood; (3) authorizes a
28 person who resides in the Windsor Park neighborhood to establish that he or she is
29 the owner of a single-family residence or a vacant lot in the Windsor Park
30 neighborhood, and, thus, is eligible to participate in the program, by executing an
31 affidavit, under penalty of perjury, or presenting certain other documentation to
32 establish inheritance or ownership of the property; (4) establishes the number of
33 new single-family residences to be constructed; (5) provides that until July 1, 2057,
34 a single-family residence acquired pursuant to the Act is entitled to an abatement of
35 a certain amount of property taxes levied on the single-family residence; (6)
36 provides an exemption from taxes on the transfer of real property for certain
37 transfers of a single-family residence pursuant to the Act; (7) requires the Housing
38 Division to file a lien on the single-family residence acquired pursuant to the Act to
39 secure repayment of certain amounts if the new residence is sold within 5 years
40 after the filing of the lien; (8) authorizes a mortgage on a single-family residence in
41 the Windsor Park neighborhood to be transferred to the new residence acquired
42 under the Act; (9) limits the amount of any assistance provided to pay off a
43 mortgage on a single-family residence in the Windsor Park neighborhood to the
44 payoff amount on May 25, 2025, unless certain circumstances exist authorizing an
45 additional amount to be paid off; (10) requires the closing of the transaction for the
46 exchange of a single-family residence or vacant lot under the Act to be an escrow
47 process with the issuance of certain title insurance and provides for the payment of
48 certain fees and charges associated with such a transaction; (11) expresses the
49 intent of the Legislature that because of the circumstances existing in the Windsor
50 Park neighborhood, for the purposes of federal income taxation, the exchange of a
51 single-family residence under the Act be considered an involuntary exchange as
52 a result of the destruction, in whole or in part, of the single-family residence or a
53 threatened requisition or condemnation; (12) requires the entity selected to develop
54 and construct a single-family residence pursuant to the Act to be engaged to
-
